liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hamish Harding, a British billionaire who served as chairman for aircraft-brokering company Action Aviation, was one of the mission specialists on the submersible and had paid to go on the expedition. The company has released a short statement, writing: "Action Aviation are united in grief with the other families who have also lost their loved ones of the Titan submersible."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'United in grief': Hamish Harding's company releases statement

children.content: Hamish Harding, a British billionaire who served as chairman for aircraft-brokering company Action Aviation, was one of the mission specialists on the submersible and had paid to go on the expedition.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Father and son Shahzada and Suleman Dawood were members of one of Pakistan's most prominent families. Following their death on board OceanGate's Titan submersible, the Dawood Foundation has released a short statement. "It is with profound grief that we announce the passing of Shahzada and Suleman Dawood who were aboard OceanGate's Titan submersible."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Dawood Foundation releases statement on 'profound grief'

children.content: Father and son Shahzada and Suleman Dawood were members of one of Pakistan's most prominent families.
Following their death on board OceanGate's Titan submersible, the Dawood Foundation has released a short statement.
"It is with profound grief that we announce the passing of Shahzada and Suleman Dawood who were aboard OceanGate's Titan submersible."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: In their statement released this morning confirming the deaths of Titan's five occupants, OceanGate called the passengers "true explorers." "We now believe that our CEO Stockton Rush, Shahzada Dawood and his son Suleman Dawood, Hamish Harding, and Paul-Henri Nargeolet, have sadly been lost." "These men were true explorers who shared a distinct spirit of adventure, and a deep passion for exploring and protecting the world's ocean."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: OceanGate calls passengers 'true explorers'
